235
00:18:07,136 --> 00:18:11,357
We're basically providing a reason for you to utilize that new skill.

236
00:18:12,239 --> 00:18:17,903
This boss particularly does a very clever psychological trick of priming.

237
00:18:17,924 --> 00:18:22,067
Because if you don't know what you need to do, you can just sit back and see the boss

238
00:18:22,648 --> 00:18:29,133
doing the same thing, and that primes you to think about grabbing it for a moment.

239
00:18:29,213 --> 00:18:32,977
Once again, this is the chain from Fury, the intro boss.

240
00:18:33,557 --> 00:18:37,521
I think bosses are perfectly capable.

241
00:18:38,561 --> 00:18:41,942
of introducing the basic mechanics.

242
00:18:42,042 --> 00:18:45,304
In this case, this boss is the first thing that you see

243
00:18:45,964 --> 00:18:52,067
and teaches you all the basic mechanics and buttons and skills.

244
00:18:56,049 --> 00:18:59,291
This is a very memorable boss, the first boss from R-Type,

245
00:18:59,671 --> 00:19:00,712
one of my favorite bosses,

246
00:19:01,112 --> 00:19:06,895
and it uses a great way of implicitly teaching you a new technique.

247
00:19:07,237 --> 00:19:12,299
In this case, the force pod that you send to infiltrate, it has this curvature there

248
00:19:12,599 --> 00:19:17,081
that keeps the force pod in the center right in front of the weak point.

249
00:19:17,181 --> 00:19:22,343
And by seeing the effect, using hindsight bias, you retain the observed result.

250
00:19:22,663 --> 00:19:27,544
That way, it reinforces the teaching of using the force pod.

251
00:19:29,145 --> 00:19:32,026
This is Ruby Weapon from Final Fantasy VII.

252
00:19:32,046 --> 00:19:36,848
It uses a great way of introducing a modified skill, in this case a handicap.

253
00:19:37,494 --> 00:19:45,986
This is the Whirlsend. It's an attack that takes party members off the game.

254
00:19:46,727 --> 00:19:50,212
And really changes the way you interact with the boss.

255
00:19:52,757 --> 00:19:56,380
Another interesting handicap is the last boss in Shadow of the Colossus.

256
00:19:57,041 --> 00:19:59,783
Following the tragic loss of your horse, Tagro,

257
00:20:00,704 --> 00:20:05,287
you don't have the speed and capabilities that the boss allows you to do,

258
00:20:05,367 --> 00:20:13,634
so you have to use evasion and stealth in the first phase of the battle.

259
00:20:14,975 --> 00:20:18,137
Increased risk. This is the last boss in Sonic 2.

260
00:20:20,961 --> 00:20:27,367
In this case, the entire level does not have any rings, which creates this illusion of

261
00:20:27,447 --> 00:20:32,912
risk and the boss feels much harder, which is a different way of playing the game.

262
00:20:34,574 --> 00:20:35,395
This is Berserker.

263
00:20:36,397 --> 00:20:42,618
In a game with a first person shooter, or a third person shooter, where all you need to do is hunt down enemies.

264
00:20:42,678 --> 00:20:52,901
In this case you can't do that, you have to lure the enemy to follow you around into the light to be hunted down by the Hammer of Dawn Death Ray.

265
00:20:55,921 --> 00:20:58,262
And this is Ray from Uncharted 4.

266
00:20:58,522 --> 00:21:01,403
And a lot of bosses use playable cutscenes basically.

267
00:21:02,179 --> 00:21:05,722
open up infinite opportunities, introduce different skills.

268
00:21:07,003 --> 00:21:14,489
This is not exactly expected, but this battle has, it's basically a glorified sword fight

269
00:21:14,869 --> 00:21:16,230
using two buttons.

270
00:21:18,746 --> 00:21:26,310
This is GLaDOS, the only boss in Portal, which introduces a new constraint.

271
00:21:26,330 --> 00:21:31,192
This is the time constraint, or at least the explicit time constraint that was not available before.

272
00:21:36,307 --> 00:21:42,451
Also, Colossus allows you to use multi-skill, combining multi-skill into one epic battle.

273
00:21:42,491 --> 00:21:50,257
This is Wheatley from 4.0.2, which forces you to use all the different things that you learn throughout the game.

274
00:21:52,438 --> 00:21:57,522
Going back to Shadow of the Colossus, this is a phased set of skills.

275
00:21:57,702 --> 00:22:01,264
Every phase has a different, unique skill that it tests.

276
00:22:01,965 --> 00:22:05,768
The first part forces you to shoot down the sacks.

277
00:22:06,335 --> 00:22:09,397
The first part is making this sand dragon drop down.

278
00:22:09,697 --> 00:22:11,958
The second part is all about timing and speed.

279
00:22:11,978 --> 00:22:17,462
The third part is holding on to the body of the dragon.

280
00:22:19,123 --> 00:22:22,966
Mr. Freeze is one of my favorite bosses, again, from the Arkham series.

281
00:22:24,286 --> 00:22:32,832
This one also tests different particular skills, but gives you the choice of how to introduce them.

282
00:22:32,912 --> 00:22:36,134
You choose when to try out every different skill.

283
00:22:37,107 --> 00:22:41,390
The boss tells you that you cannot use that anymore.

284
00:22:41,490 --> 00:22:43,931
He's going to be protected from that.

285
00:22:44,312 --> 00:22:47,654
Which is, I believe, a great way of testing out different skills.

286
00:22:50,076 --> 00:22:51,617
And of course, the side skills.

287
00:22:52,278 --> 00:22:59,983
In a game that's all about space battles, in this case, the skill is to get a triple 7.

288
00:23:00,023 --> 00:23:00,423
In space.

289
00:23:05,961 --> 00:23:14,263
In Metroid Prime, which is a 3D action-adventure game, you get kind of a glimpse to a different game.

290
00:23:14,783 --> 00:23:23,605
Spider Guardian is basically a 2D puzzle game, which is again something that only a boss battle can do, if you think about it.

291
00:23:26,365 --> 00:23:30,486
One of my favorites, this is The Bride from Miss Explosion Man.

292
00:23:31,046 --> 00:23:34,587
This is a side skill that's a tribute to Hat-Tip.

293
00:23:35,326 --> 00:23:37,227
If you will, to another game.

294
00:23:37,247 --> 00:23:39,827
This is basically a tribute to Punch-Out!!

295
00:23:44,449 --> 00:23:49,851
And this is from last year, Dr. Robotnik's Mindy Machine from Sonic Mania.

296
00:23:50,111 --> 00:23:54,072
Which is another glimpse to a different game.

297
00:23:54,112 --> 00:23:57,433
A game with the same name, which is essentially a session of Puyo Puyo.

298
00:23:59,494 --> 00:24:01,674
Alright, let's move on to the actual confrontation.

299
00:24:02,615 --> 00:24:04,015
Alright, so...

300
00:24:05,747 --> 00:24:10,388
We will be talking about how to design attack patterns around the tested skill that we just established

301
00:24:10,568 --> 00:24:13,209
and how to encourage interaction between the boss and the player.

302
00:24:15,450 --> 00:24:24,673
Dracula from Castlevania is a boss that basically tests jumping and hitting from very close range.

303
00:24:25,614 --> 00:24:30,695
In order to support that skill, the attack pattern is designed to be very precise.

304
00:24:31,044 --> 00:24:39,150
uses the negative space that is left by that skill and forces the player to get very close

305
00:24:39,610 --> 00:24:46,975
to the boss and jump over it. So if you think about it, we are using and complementing the

306
00:24:47,035 --> 00:24:54,220
skill that we've established. Cuphead from last year did a fantastic job in pretty much every boss

307
00:24:54,961 --> 00:24:59,444
in establishing a skill, a specific skill, and then creating a negative space that forces you

308
00:25:01,208 --> 00:25:07,014
to interact in a certain way.

309
00:25:08,336 --> 00:25:13,161
Bosses, bullet hells like Don and Pachi, that Krattsu...

310
00:25:13,755 --> 00:25:18,636
is a great example of the idea of negative space.

311
00:25:18,756 --> 00:25:20,757
Because if you think about it, and as we can see,

312
00:25:21,337 --> 00:25:23,598
the boss can kill you whenever they want.

313
00:25:23,778 --> 00:25:28,079
If the designers wished to kill you, they would just shoot an endless amount of bullets

314
00:25:28,219 --> 00:25:31,220
or end the boss with an infinite speed.

315
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:35,822
But in this case, we are actually trying to not kill the player.

316
00:25:35,842 --> 00:25:37,182
We're planning how to keep them alive.

317
00:25:37,322 --> 00:25:41,783
And you can see that even within the bullet hell, there are paths.

318
00:25:42,395 --> 00:25:44,435
that are allowed for the player to use.

319
00:25:46,436 --> 00:25:48,736
So that's what we're planning. We're planning the paths.

320
00:25:51,457 --> 00:25:54,818
Another great example is from Contra.

321
00:25:54,878 --> 00:26:00,479
Pretty much a lot of the bosses there create the idea of the counter-attack.

322
00:26:01,740 --> 00:26:04,661
So you are attacking the boss as they attack you.

323
00:26:05,741 --> 00:26:09,082
And that creates kind of a poetic justice, of course.

324
00:26:09,162 --> 00:26:10,662
But also there's a...

325
00:26:11,601 --> 00:26:16,764
There's an element here that's very useful for designing a boss, which is creating this

326
00:26:16,905 --> 00:26:22,489
short time window and a limited space, which forces us to have this confrontation and this

327
00:26:22,569 --> 00:26:24,570
cycle of evading and attacking.

328
00:26:28,133 --> 00:26:30,875
We saw the King Kupama from N64.

329
00:26:30,895 --> 00:26:36,639
This is the DS version, which is pretty much exactly the same idea.

330
00:26:36,739 --> 00:26:39,301
It teaches you how to grab and throw.

331
00:26:39,774 --> 00:26:41,675
but it uses a completely different way.

332
00:26:41,695 --> 00:26:45,218
It throws a bomb at you, which again is kind of a cliche of bosses,

333
00:26:45,698 --> 00:26:46,959
but it...

334
00:26:47,719 --> 00:26:47,899
it...

335
00:26:48,900 --> 00:26:52,863
this deflection that it requires puts the player in the line of fire

336
00:26:53,123 --> 00:26:56,885
and forces this interaction between the boss and the player.

337
00:26:56,905 --> 00:27:03,630
One of my favorite bosses, at least from the Zelda series, is Drinrova,

338
00:27:03,950 --> 00:27:08,093
which again creates... forces this interaction between you...

339
00:27:08,546 --> 00:27:13,067
And the bosses, in this case, you deflect the attack of one sister against the other.

340
00:27:13,227 --> 00:27:21,569
One of my favorite bosses, Eusticia from Bayonetta, in another game with fantastic bosses.

341
00:27:22,289 --> 00:27:24,910
In this case, it's another type of counterattack.

342
00:27:24,970 --> 00:27:26,050
It creates a path...

343
00:27:28,031 --> 00:27:30,431
By attacking you, it creates a path for its own destruction.

344
00:27:31,792 --> 00:27:36,713
Another version of that can be found in Dingo Dial from Crash Bandicoot Warped.

345
00:27:37,909 --> 00:27:44,171
You lure Dingo Dial to shoot at you, thus creating a path that you can use to destroy him.

346
00:27:45,851 --> 00:27:52,434
And you can see also that the arena, in this case, was perfectly tailored for this specific battle,

347
00:27:52,474 --> 00:27:55,175
which leads us to the arena layout.

348
00:27:55,275 --> 00:28:01,537
Again, we're trying to create an arena that complements the battle and is based on that specific fight.

349
00:28:02,057 --> 00:28:03,817
This is Cyberdemon from Doom from 2016.

350
00:28:06,033 --> 00:28:12,979
In both phases of the battle, the arena is very small, open, no place to hide,

351
00:28:14,200 --> 00:28:19,824
kind of reminiscent of olden times as well, and it increases the confrontation.

352
00:28:19,844 --> 00:28:27,130
And further, so during the second phase, it uses this temporary layout change

353
00:28:27,170 --> 00:28:32,695
that even creates this lane that restricts your motion.

354
00:28:33,683 --> 00:28:37,304
and makes the confrontation even more obvious.

355
00:28:40,245 --> 00:28:50,148
But the idea is that the arena is always designed and tailored to that specific boss battle.

356
00:28:50,208 --> 00:28:53,929
This is a boss that moves extremely fast and is partially invisible.

357
00:28:54,449 --> 00:28:55,349
You don't know where the...

358
00:28:57,070 --> 00:29:00,091
By looking where the attacks come from, you know where the boss would be.

359
00:29:00,151 --> 00:29:02,472
And also they made a lot of fences and...

360
00:29:02,904 --> 00:29:09,267
There are also a bunch of different hubs for interaction.

361
00:29:13,129 --> 00:29:18,232
Lighting can also be used as a great way of introducing a layout.

362
00:29:19,052 --> 00:29:25,095
In this case, the Specter Knight boss in Shovel Knight uses the shadows to hide.

363
00:29:25,255 --> 00:29:32,019
And if you haven't noticed how it moves in the first phase of the fight, you wouldn't even know how to interact with it.

364
00:29:32,725 --> 00:29:35,226
So it kind of teaches and then tests your ability.

365
00:29:37,748 --> 00:29:41,951
And one of the most important points in boss battles is the attack space.

366
00:29:42,131 --> 00:29:49,415
And I'm referring to the idea that you can employ multiple approaches or strategies against the boss.

367
00:29:49,515 --> 00:29:58,000
I think a good boss can be beaten in multiple ways, or at least different players can interact with it in different ways.

368
00:29:58,821 --> 00:30:01,743
In this case, this is Ornstein and Smough from Dark Souls.

369
00:30:02,834 --> 00:30:08,915
A fantastic boss that is particularly remembered because of the two bosses really.

370
00:30:09,195 --> 00:30:15,617
One of them is quick and weak and the other one is very powerful and slow.

371
00:30:15,957 --> 00:30:21,458
And you choose how to interact with that boss and you form your own strategy.

372
00:30:23,618 --> 00:30:27,879
I'm not a huge RPG player but this is also a memorable.

373
00:30:28,392 --> 00:30:32,154
It's a boss battle, this Archimon from Dark Dragon Age Origins.

374
00:30:32,755 --> 00:30:38,358
It's also known for its various different strategies that can be used in order to beat the boss.

375
00:30:40,759 --> 00:30:42,440
Once again, Big Daddy.

376
00:30:42,560 --> 00:30:48,563
It's one of the first games that allows you to have these different approaches and mobs and emerging behaviors.

377
00:30:48,683 --> 00:30:52,965
You can beat Big Daddy by using shotguns, electricity...

378
00:30:54,846 --> 00:31:01,609
telekinetically moving booby traps, and even hypnotizing one Big Daddy against another.

379
00:31:03,610 --> 00:31:08,893
Alright, moving on to clarity. We need to make sure that we avoid unpredictability,

380
00:31:08,933 --> 00:31:13,896
obscurity, and randomness by setting clear goals, progression in hits, and predictable attacks.

381
00:31:14,756 --> 00:31:21,720
So, the idea of a clear target is very obvious. We all know that we've kind of gotten used to the idea of a glowing target.

382
00:31:22,237 --> 00:31:25,699
a weak spot which creates a clear vulnerability and a call to action.

383
00:31:25,759 --> 00:31:29,720
There's even a funny article from The Onion exactly on that.

384
00:31:32,181 --> 00:31:35,422
Creating a clear call to action is extremely important.

385
00:31:35,482 --> 00:31:37,803
This is an example from Shadow of the Colossus.

386
00:31:38,123 --> 00:31:42,645
Particularly when you have a large boss with multiple weak points, the sigils,

387
00:31:43,925 --> 00:31:47,747
it forces us as designers to create some sort of guidance as needed.

388
00:31:48,747 --> 00:31:51,188
In this case, the sword that lights up the next target.

389
00:31:52,969 --> 00:31:57,311
In some cases, guidance is not needed. This is Dark Link.

390
00:31:59,413 --> 00:32:09,499
You don't need to know its particular weak spots because it is you. You know its strengths and weaknesses.

391
00:32:09,539 --> 00:32:13,841
This reminded me of Mirror Prince from Prince of Persia.

392
00:32:13,901 --> 00:32:19,024
The first phase, the first part of the game, you create this Mirror Prince by going through a mirror.

393
00:32:19,789 --> 00:32:22,930
The second part, you have to battle it.

394
00:32:23,730 --> 00:32:27,852
And in this case, the challenge is a logical challenge,

395
00:32:27,912 --> 00:32:33,213
figuring out how to beat it by lowering your sword and moving into him.

396
00:32:33,373 --> 00:32:38,595
And this is the puzzle battle, and I really enjoy bosses that employ logic.

397
00:32:39,555 --> 00:32:41,916
And figuring out the goal is the challenge in this case.

398
00:32:42,296 --> 00:32:46,757
And one thing that's very, very important, and I can talk a lot about this,

399
00:32:46,857 --> 00:32:48,498
and I don't want to spend too much time on it,

400
00:32:48,618 --> 00:32:49,238
the idea is that...

401
00:32:49,728 --> 00:32:55,133
You either employ logic or skill, but try to avoid doing both at the same exact time.

402
00:32:56,814 --> 00:33:00,717
The reason is what I call the delta of chance, and I'm going to talk about that later.

403
00:33:01,018 --> 00:33:06,702
Delta of chance is that when you believe that you've succeeded and then immediately fail

404
00:33:06,742 --> 00:33:14,229
because there's an additional challenge and vice versa. That creates a very unsatisfying moment.

405
00:33:16,511 --> 00:33:17,311
Clear progression.

406
00:33:18,260 --> 00:33:23,923
We talked about the glowing red point, which creates a focal call to action.

407
00:33:24,683 --> 00:33:33,067
We can also see that this particular game, and most games of the time, have a clear hit.

408
00:33:33,327 --> 00:33:35,728
You can see a couple of frames that change the color.

409
00:33:36,789 --> 00:33:43,191
And also, of course, the health bar, which we've all grown accustomed to in many bosses.

410
00:33:44,632 --> 00:33:45,513
Not every boss has...

411
00:33:46,877 --> 00:33:52,339
Health bars, in some cases, you don't really need it, as long as you have a clear understanding of how far you've gotten.

412
00:33:52,359 --> 00:33:56,480
This is the first phase of Hive Mind in Dead Space.

413
00:33:56,520 --> 00:33:59,841
There are a couple of pods that you... five pods that you need to destroy,

414
00:34:00,221 --> 00:34:04,122
and by seeing how many you have left, you have a clear understanding of the progression.

415
00:34:06,302 --> 00:34:09,483
Early... in the early games, this is a space harrier.

416
00:34:09,503 --> 00:34:12,364
They used a kind of a weird trick of changing the color.

417
00:34:13,063 --> 00:34:15,865
of the boss as they lose health.

418
00:34:17,207 --> 00:34:19,709
But that trick has been long gone.

419
00:34:19,729 --> 00:34:22,912
It limits your visual design abilities.

420
00:34:24,733 --> 00:34:30,558
An interesting way of presenting your progression is done in Cuphead.

421
00:34:31,799 --> 00:34:34,582
So instead of showing you the progression during the battle,

422
00:34:34,622 --> 00:34:36,143
they do it when you die.

423
00:34:36,504 --> 00:34:38,686
Which, if you think about it, is actually quite clever because

424
00:34:38,706 --> 00:34:39,406
you...

425
00:34:40,840 --> 00:34:44,141
potentially lose players just before a potential rage quit.

426
00:34:44,901 --> 00:34:46,462
They can see how far they've gotten.

427
00:34:46,942 --> 00:34:49,543
So that's a very interesting prospect.

428
00:34:50,103 --> 00:34:53,784
It also shows you the phase which gives you even further indication of where you are.

429
00:34:55,844 --> 00:34:57,925
Talking about Cuphead,

430
00:34:58,665 --> 00:35:01,506
it's incredibly important to have a predictable attack

431
00:35:02,506 --> 00:35:05,187
because predictability is control

432
00:35:05,407 --> 00:35:07,627
and when you know how the bullets,

433
00:35:07,647 --> 00:35:09,828
you can have many different bullets or attack types.

434
00:35:10,892 --> 00:35:17,135
Go in the next frame you have control over the battle and as long as you have information and time to react

435
00:35:17,916 --> 00:35:19,036
You can beat any boss

436
00:35:20,717 --> 00:35:26,640
Some bosses kind of put you in a position where you don't have enough time. This is again the first boss in

437
00:35:26,880 --> 00:35:29,762
Shinobi which is notorious for its

438
00:35:30,322 --> 00:35:35,985
Randomness in the attacks. I think in this case. They actually wanted to create this panic

439
00:35:37,705 --> 00:35:41,206
in order to force the player to use the magic.

440
00:35:42,387 --> 00:35:44,388
But generally, randomness is very risky.

441
00:35:45,868 --> 00:35:48,189
Going back to Space Harrier,

442
00:35:48,410 --> 00:35:51,871
another interesting point is that

443
00:35:53,792 --> 00:35:56,853
while in 2D it's very clear to see an attack coming,

444
00:35:56,873 --> 00:35:59,755
it's very clear to extrapolate its position,

445
00:36:01,917 --> 00:36:04,438
In 3D it's not that easy.

446
00:36:04,718 --> 00:36:10,881
I think we've evolved in a way that a change in scale is not that visible.

447
00:36:12,522 --> 00:36:14,843
Some 3D games do it better.

448
00:36:16,304 --> 00:36:19,485
So, going back to Cyberdemon,

449
00:36:19,825 --> 00:36:24,967
as long as it's visible enough that something is going directly at you,

450
00:36:26,268 --> 00:36:27,388
then you should be fine.

451
00:36:27,428 --> 00:36:30,310
In this case, the flare behind the rocket

452
00:36:30,649 --> 00:36:35,192
gives you just enough information to know if an attack is coming directly at you.

453
00:36:38,073 --> 00:36:40,535
Another cool trick from the Barbas fight,

454
00:36:40,555 --> 00:36:45,097
it always attacks you sideways and then clamping towards you,

455
00:36:45,477 --> 00:36:49,960
again giving you just enough information and time to react.

456
00:36:54,202 --> 00:36:57,644
But you don't always have enough information or time to react,

457
00:36:59,582 --> 00:37:01,523
You have to compensate with enough information.

458
00:37:02,423 --> 00:37:09,645
The preemptive shadow, as I call it here, is highlighting where the hit is going to land.

459
00:37:09,865 --> 00:37:16,326
This is both the fireballs and the bombs as well.

460
00:37:17,166 --> 00:37:22,768
If you think about it, it kind of compensates for the lack of information that we, as spectators, have.

461
00:37:23,918 --> 00:37:29,882
If Mario can look up and see the bombs falling, we don't have that luxury, so by providing

462
00:37:29,922 --> 00:37:35,965
