00:41:38,258 --> 00:41:40,618
from it's pretty recent that they

519
00:41:41,199 --> 00:41:44,760
studied this neurotransmitter and realized that its behavior

520
00:41:45,786 --> 00:41:52,151
really rewards and encourages behavior that leads to a positive change in your behavior.

521
00:41:53,932 --> 00:42:02,739
And there's always kind of a low dosage of dopamine that changes, peaks when you have

522
00:42:02,759 --> 00:42:06,863
this positive delta of chance and completely stops when you have the negative delta of

523
00:42:06,903 --> 00:42:14,168
chance kind of in an evolutionary way of teaching you how to work and advance in the world.

524
00:42:15,025 --> 00:42:20,470
In our world, you can kind of imagine that if you think about playing a game of Tetris,

525
00:42:20,870 --> 00:42:25,554
where you can see that you're almost going to fail, and then you see that the next piece is a long piece.

526
00:42:26,735 --> 00:42:34,341
Sometimes you would want to kind of wait and extend that amazing moment that you know that you've just survived.

527
00:42:35,041 --> 00:42:41,987
And that feeling is what I believe is one of the most important and one of the biggest takeaways I think you should have from this talk.

528
00:42:42,577 --> 00:42:48,819
And this is something that I also learned kind of recently, because I made a game that is extremely difficult. You probably know that.

529
00:42:50,319 --> 00:42:59,801
The idea of making sure that there's a challenging peak followed by a kind of anticipated triumph is extremely important.

530
00:42:59,941 --> 00:43:03,422
And I can see this in pretty much all the good bosses that I surveyed.

